      "slideId": 1,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "The Linux File System Structure"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "The Linux file system structure is the organized layout used by Linux to store files and directories, starting from a single root directory and branching into standard system folders."
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Single root directory /",
            "Hierarchical (tree-like) structure",
            "Case-sensitive file names",
            "Everything is treated as a file"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "video": null
    },
    {
      "slideId": 2,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Key Features of Linux File System"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "This structured approach helps Linux manage system files, user data, applications, and hardware efficiently."
        }
      ],
      "video": null
    },
    {
      "slideId": 3,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Important Linux Directories"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "/ – Root directory",
            "/home – User home directories",
            "/bin – Essential user commands",
            "/sbin – System administration commands",
            "/etc – Configuration files",
            "/var – Variable data like logs",
            "/tmp – Temporary files",
            "/usr – User applications and libraries"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "video": null
    },
    {
      "slideId": 4,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Path"
        },
        {
          "type": "definition",
          "value": "A path is the location of a file or directory in the Linux file system.",
          "example": "Example: /home/user/file.txt"
        }
      ],
      "video": null
    },
    {
      "slideId": 5,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Absolute and Relative Paths"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "An absolute path starts from the root directory / and shows the full location of a file or directory, regardless of the current working directory."
        }
      ],
      "video": null
    },
    {
      "slideId": 6,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Code – Viewing Directory Structure"
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "value": [
            "ls /",
            "ls /home",
            "tree /"
          ]
        }
      ],
